      "title": "Point wrt hyperbola",
      "conceptBody": "<p><strong>Position of a point P w.r.t. hyperbola</strong></p><p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" width=\"287\" height=\"208\"></p><p>Let $\\text{S}=0$ be the hyperbola and $\\text{P}\\left( {{\\text{x}}_{1}},{{\\text{y}}_{1}} \\right)$ be the point and ${{\\text{S}}_{1}}\\equiv \\text{S}\\left( {{\\text{x}}_{1}},{{\\text{y}}_{1}} \\right)$.</p><p>Then</p><p>${{\\text{S}}_{1}}&lt;0\\Rightarrow \\text{P}$ is in the exterior region.</p><p>${{\\text{S}}_{1}}&gt;0\\Rightarrow \\text{P}$ is in the interior region.</p><p>${{\\text{S}}_{1}}=0\\Rightarrow \\text{P}$ lies on the hyperbola.</p><p><strong>Important:&nbsp;</strong></p><p>Note that most of the results proved for hyperbola $\\frac{{{x}^{2}}}{{{a}^{2}}}-\\frac{{{y}^{2}}}{{{b}^{2}}}=1$ can be obtained from the same formula for ellipse $\\frac{{{x}^{2}}}{{{a}^{2}}}+\\frac{{{y}^{2}}}{{{b}^{2}}}=1$, by replacing ${{b}^{2}}$ by $-{{b}^{2}}$ in conditions for ellipse.</p><p><strong>Q) Show that the equation ${{x}^{2}}-2{{y}^{2}}-2x+8y-1=0$ represents a hyperbola. Find the coordinates of the center, lengths of the axes, eccentricity, latus rectum, coordinates of the foci and vertices and equations of directrices of the hyperbola.&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>Solution:&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>$\\begin{array}{*{35}{r}} &nbsp;{} &amp; {{\\text{x}}^{2}}-2{{\\text{y}}^{2}}-2\\text{x}+8\\text{y}-1=0 \\\\ {} &amp; ~\\Rightarrow \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }\\left( {{\\text{x}}^{2}}-2\\text{x} \\right)-2\\left( {{\\text{y}}^{2}}-4\\text{y} \\right)=1 \\\\ {} &amp; ~\\Rightarrow \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }\\left( {{\\text{x}}^{2}}-2\\text{x}+1 \\right)-2\\left( {{\\text{y}}^{2}}-4\\text{y}+4 \\right)=-6 \\\\ {} &amp; ~\\Rightarrow \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{(\\text{x}-1)}^{2}}-2{{(\\text{y}-2)}^{2}}=-6 \\\\ &nbsp;{} &amp; ~\\Rightarrow \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }\\frac{{{(\\text{x}-1)}^{2}}}{{{(\\sqrt{6})}^{2}}}-\\frac{{{(\\text{y}-2)}^{2}}}{\\left( \\sqrt{3} \\right)}=-1\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }\\ldots \\left( \\text{i} \\right) \\\\ \\end{array}$&nbsp;</strong></p><p>Shifting the origin at $\\left( 1,2 \\right)$ without rotating the coordinates axes and denoting the new coordinates with respect to these axes by $\\text{X}$ and $\\text{Y}$, we have</p><p>$\\text{x}=\\text{X}+1\\text{ and }\\text{ y}=\\text{Y}+2$ …(ii)</p><p>Using these relations, equation (i) reduces to</p><p>$\\frac{{{\\text{X}}^{2}}}{{{(\\sqrt{6})}^{2}}}-\\frac{{{\\text{Y}}^{2}}}{{{(\\sqrt{3})}^{2}}}=-1$ …(iii)</p><p>This equation is of the form $\\frac{{{X}^{2}}}{{{a}^{2}}}-\\frac{{{Y}^{2}}}{{{b}^{2}}}=-1$, where ${{a}^{2}}={{(\\sqrt{6})}^{2}}$ and ${{b}^{2}}={{(\\sqrt{3})}^{2}}$. So, we have:</p><p><strong>Centre </strong>The coordinates of the center with respect to the new axes are $\\left( X=0,Y=0 \\right)$.</p><p>So, the coordinates of the center with respect to the old axes are $\\left( 1,2 \\right)$ [Putting $\\text{X}=0,\\text{Y}=0$ in (ii)]</p><p><strong>Lengths of the Axes </strong>: Since the transverse axis of the hyperbola is along new Y-axis.</p><p>$\\therefore \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }$ Transverse axis $=2\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ b}=2\\sqrt{3}$, Conjugate axis $=2\\text{a}=2\\sqrt{6}$.</p><p><strong>Eccentricity </strong>: The eccentricity e is given by $e=\\sqrt{1+\\frac{{{\\text{a}}^{2}}}{\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{b}}^{2}}}}=\\sqrt{1+\\frac{6}{3}}=\\sqrt{3}$</p><p><strong>Latus rectum: </strong>Length of the latus rectum $=\\frac{2{{\\text{a}}^{2}}}{\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ b}}=\\frac{12}{\\sqrt{3}}=4\\sqrt{3}$.</p><p><strong>Foci </strong>: The coordinates of foci with respect to the new axes are $(\\text{X}=0,\\text{Y}=\\pm \\text{ be) }\\text{ i}\\text{.e}\\text{. }\\left( \\text{X}=0,\\text{Y}=\\pm 3 \\right)\\text{. }$</p><p>So, the coordinates of the vertices with respect to the old axes are $\\left( 1,2\\pm 3 \\right)$ i.e. $\\left( 1,5 \\right)$ and $\\left( 1,-1 \\right)$ [Putting $\\text{X}=0,\\text{Y}=\\pm 3$ in (ii)]</p><p><strong>Vertices </strong>: The coordinates of the vertices with respect to the new axes are $\\text{X}=0,\\text{Y}=\\pm \\text{b}$ i.e., $\\left( \\text{X}=0,\\text{Y}=\\pm \\sqrt{3} \\right)$</p><p>So, the coordinates of the vertices w.r.t. to the old axes are.</p><p>$\\left( 1,2\\pm \\sqrt{3} \\right)\\text{ i}\\text{.e}\\text{. }\\left( 1,2+\\sqrt{3} \\right)\\text{ and }\\left( 1,2-\\sqrt{3} \\right)[\\text{ Putting }\\text{ X}=0,\\text{Y}=+\\sqrt{3}\\text{ in }\\text{ (ii)}]$</p><p><strong>Directrices </strong>: The equations of the directrices with respect to the new axes are $\\text{Y}=\\pm $ b/e i.e., $\\text{Y}=\\pm 1$</p><p>So, the equations of the directrices with respect to the old axes are</p><p>$\\text{y}=2\\pm 1$ i.e., $\\text{y}=1$ and $\\text{y}=3$ [Putting $\\text{Y}=\\pm 2$ in (ii)]</p><p><strong>Q) If $\\text{e}$ and $\\text{{e}'}$ be the eccentricities of a hyperbola and its conjugate, prove that $\\frac{1}{{{\\text{e}}^{2}}}+\\frac{1}{{{\\text{e}}^{2}}}=1$.&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>Solution:&nbsp;</strong></p><p>Let the equation of the hyperbola be $\\frac{{{x}^{2}}}{{{a}^{2}}}-\\frac{{{y}^{2}}}{{{b}^{2}}}=1$ …(i)</p><p>Then the equation of the hyperbola conjugate to (i) is $\\frac{{{x}^{2}}}{{{a}^{2}}}-\\frac{{{y}^{2}}}{{{b}^{2}}}=-1$ …(ii)</p><p>$\\text{e}=$ Eccentricity of $\\left( \\text{i} \\right)=\\sqrt{1+{{\\left( \\frac{\\text{ conjugate }\\text{ axis }}{\\text{ Transverse }\\text{ axis }} \\right)}^{2}}}$</p><p>$\\Rightarrow \\text{ e}=\\sqrt{1+{{\\left( \\frac{2b}{2a} \\right)}^{2}}}\\Rightarrow {{\\text{e}}^{2}}=1+\\frac{{{\\text{b}}^{2}}}{{{\\text{a}}^{2}}}\\Rightarrow {{\\text{e}}^{2}}=\\frac{{{\\text{a}}^{2}}+{{\\text{b}}^{2}}}{{{\\text{a}}^{2}}}$ …(iii)</p><p>And, $\\text{{e}'}=$ Eccentricity of $\\left( \\text{ii} \\right)=\\sqrt{1+{{\\left( \\frac{\\text{ conjugate }\\text{ axis }}{\\text{ Transverse }\\text{ axis }} \\right)}^{2}}}$</p><p>$\\Rightarrow \\text{ {e}'}=\\sqrt{1+{{\\left( \\frac{2\\text{a}}{2\\text{ b}} \\right)}^{2}}}\\Rightarrow {{\\text{e}}^{'2}}=1+\\frac{{{\\text{a}}^{2}}}{{{\\text{b}}^{2}}}\\Rightarrow {{\\text{e}}^{-2}}=\\frac{{{\\text{a}}^{2}}+{{\\text{b}}^{2}}}{{{\\text{b}}^{2}}}$ …(iv)</p><p>From (iii) and (iv), we have</p><p>$\\frac{1}{{{\\text{e}}^{2}}}+\\frac{1}{{{\\text{e}}^{'2}}}=\\frac{{{\\text{a}}^{2}}}{{{\\text{a}}^{2}}+{{\\text{b}}^{2}}}+\\frac{{{\\text{b}}^{2}}}{{{\\text{a}}^{2}}+{{\\text{b}}^{2}}}=\\frac{{{\\text{a}}^{2}}+{{\\text{b}}^{2}}}{{{\\text{a}}^{2}}+{{\\text{b}}^{2}}}\\Rightarrow \\frac{1}{{{\\text{e}}^{2}}}+\\frac{1}{{{\\text{e}}^{'2}}}=1$</p>",
